def find_each_class(labels):
    # Creates a list in which the first occurence of each class is stored.
    indexes_for_each_label = list() 
    
    for label in range(10):
        index = np.where(labels==label)[0][0] 
        indexes_for_each_label.append(index) # Add index where the corresponding label was found to list
    
    # Index in this list: Class. Value in this list: First occurrence in np array 'labels'. 
    return indexes_for_each_label

%matplotlib inline 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def print_dataset(images, labels, columns, rows, dataset_name):
    # Creates one large figure (to put the smaller in it)
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(columns*3, 6))
    plt.title('Visualization of ' + str(dataset_name) + '\n\n', fontweight = "bold")
    plt.axis('off')
    imgs = []
    
    # Iterates through the images and add them as subs to figure
    for i in range(1, columns*rows+1):
        for index in find_each_class(labels):
            img = images[index]
            imgs.append(img)
        fig.add_subplot(rows, columns, i)
        plt.title('Class ' + str(i-1))
        plt.axis('off')
        plt.imshow(imgs[i-1])

    plt.show()

print_dataset(images, labels, 5, 2, 'Training Set')

In [6]:
from torchvision.transforms import Resize, ToTensor, Normalize, Compose

class ATMLDatasetWrapper(torch.utils.data.Dataset):
    ''' Wrapper class for given dataset '''
    def __init__(self, dataset, labels):
        self.transforms = Compose([ToTensor(), Normalize(mean=(0.5, 0.5, 0.5,), std=(0.5, 0.5, 0.5)),])
        self.data = [self.transforms(sample) for sample in dataset]
        self.labels = labels # Different to example of Tutorial 3
        self.n = len(dataset)
        
    def __getitem__(self, ind):
        return self.data[ind], self.labels[ind]
    
    def __len__(self):
        return self.n

In [8]:
import torch.nn as nn
class LinearModel(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self, input_dim):
        super(LinearModel, self).__init__()
        self.fc = nn.Linear(input_dim, 10, bias=True) # 10 since we have 10 classes
        
    def forward(self, input):
        out = input.view(input.size(0), -1) # To batch_size x (3 * height * width)
        out = self.fc(out) # Applies out = input * A + b where A, b are parameters to learn.
        return out
In [9]:
def train_epoch(model, train_dataloader, optimizer, loss_fn):
    # Initialize losses and correct predictions counter
    losses = []
    correct_predictions = 0
    
    # Iterate mini batches over training dataset
    for images, labels in train_dataloader:
        images = images.to(device)
        labels = labels.to(device)
        output = model(images) # Predictions
        optimizer.zero_grad() # Set gradients to 0
        loss = loss_fn(output, labels) # Compute loss
        loss.backward() # With backpropagation compute gradients
        optimizer.step() # Optimization step -> Update of weights
        losses.append(loss.item())
        predicted_labels = output.argmax(dim=1) # Precicted class
        correct_predictions += (predicted_labels == labels).sum().item() # Update amount of correct predictions (if possible)
        
    accuracy = 100.0 * correct_predictions / len(train_dataloader.dataset) # Compute accuracy
    mean_loss = np.array(losses).mean() # Compute the mean 
    
    # Return metrics of epoch
    return mean_loss, accuracy
In [10]:
def evaluate(model, dataloader, loss_fn):
    # Initialize losses and correct predictions counter
    losses = []
    correct_predictions = 0
    
    with torch.no_grad():
        for images, labels in dataloader:
            images = images.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            output = model(images) # Predictions
            loss = loss_fn(output, labels) # Compute loss
            predicted_labels = output.argmax(dim=1) # Predicted class
            correct_predictions += (predicted_labels == labels).sum().item() # Update amount of correct predictions (if possible)
            losses.append(loss.item()) # Add the computed loss to losses
            
    mean_loss = np.array(losses).mean()
    accuracy = 100.0 * correct_predictions / len(dataloader.dataset)
    
    return mean_loss, accuracy
In [11]:
def train(model, train_dataloader, val_dataloader, optimizer, n_epochs, loss_function):
    # Save metrics as the training progresses
    train_losses, val_losses, train_accuracies, val_accuracies = ([] for i in range(4))

    for epoch in range(n_epochs):
        model.train() # Model goes to train
        train_loss, train_accuracy = train_epoch(model, train_dataloader, optimizer, loss_fn) # Train model for 1 epoch
        model.eval() # Model goes to evaluating
        val_loss, val_accuracy = evaluate(model, val_dataloader, loss_fn) # Computation of metrics
        
        # Append computed values to corresponding list
        train_losses.append(train_loss)
        val_losses.append(val_loss)
        train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)
        val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)
        print('Epoch {}/{}: train_loss: {:.4f}, train_accuracy: {:.4f}, val_loss: {:.4f}, val_accuracy: {:.4f}'.format(epoch+1, n_epochs,
                                                                                                      train_losses[-1],
                                                                                                      train_accuracies[-1],
                                                                                                      val_losses[-1],
                                                                                                      val_accuracies[-1]))
    return train_losses, val_losses, train_accuracies, val_accuracies
In [12]:
def sub_plotting(learning_rate, n_epochs, train_metr, val_metr, metric_name):
    plt.figure()
    plt.title('Model\'s ' + str(metric_name) + ' with Learning Rate = ' + str(learning_rate), fontweight='bold')
    plt.plot(list(range(1,n_epochs+1)), train_metr, label='Training')
    plt.plot(list(range(1,n_epochs+1)), val_metr, label='Validation')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel(str(metric_name))
    plt.legend()
    plt.xticks(np.arange(1, n_epochs+1, 1.0))

# Initialize loss function, amount of epochs and learning rates
# Optimizer will be initialized depending on learning rate, therefore below in loop
loss_fn = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss() # Use PyTorch's CrossEntropyLoss function
n_epochs = 15 
learning_rates = [0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001]

# We examine multiple models
models, losses = ([] for i in range(2)) 

for i, learning_rate in enumerate(learning_rates):
    model = LinearModel(64*64*3) # 64 pixels
    model = model.to(device)
    models.append(model) # Append the current model to the multiple models we examine

    # Training part with the current learning rate
    print('\nModel is trained with learning rate: ' + str(learning_rate)) 
    optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate) # Use appropriate optimizer from torch
    train_losses, val_losses, train_acc, val_acc = train(model, train_dataloader, val_dataloader, optimizer, n_epochs, loss_fn)
    
    # Plotting
    sub_plotting(learning_rate, n_epochs, train_losses, val_losses, 'Loss')
    sub_plotting(learning_rate, n_epochs, train_acc, val_acc, 'Accuracy')     
        
    # Save validation loss of last epoch
    losses.append(val_losses[-1]) 


# Plotting
plt.show()

# Select best model based on results on validation set (smallest loss, last epoch)
best_model = models[np.argmin(losses)]

class_weights = []

for i in range(10):
    class_weight = best_model.fc.weight[i].view(64, 64, 3).detach().cpu().numpy()
    class_weight = np.mean(class_weight, axis=2)
    class_weight = (class_weight - class_weight.min()) / class_weight.max() # normalize
    class_weights.append(class_weight)

print_dataset(class_weights, np.arange(10), 5, 2, 'Learned Weights') # np arange since list range doesn't work

Report below:¶

REPORT: Compare validation and test acccuracy. Comment on differences.
How are test images different from train images?
Visualize weights of your best linear model. What did the model learn? How does it distinguish images? Why does it fail on test images?

As suspected the accuracy on the trainning set is lower than before, but it is oddly low with only 10% (on validation set 100% !!). Therefore one can conclude that the model didn't learn something meaningful to use in classification.

Since on the validation set the accuracy is much better I suppose the underlying problem is somewhat of a different distribution of images in validation and test set. Unfortunately there is no visible proof concerning the "causal content" while printing the images from train and test set.

With visualization of the weights one can see an occuring pattern that is used for the classification: The special pixels are always on the same height/position. Since the question is explicitely "Why does it fail on test images" and because of the visualizations I assume there was some information added explicitely to lead the model to fail. While looking closer on the images one can see that the first row of each image doesn't complete the image in a meaningful way, it is rather one line of black pixels with some white ones in it.

Task 4. Fix the observed problem¶

My proposal is to remove this black line and retrain the model.

> Comparison of training, val and test loss and accuracy with the previous mode:
Previously the values for were:
Loss = 0.0001, Acc = 100.00 (train), Loss = 0.0021, Acc = 100.00 (val), Loss = 10.0732, Acc = 10.7625 (test)
Now they are:
Loss = 1.5111, Acc = 48.6667 (train), Loss = 1.7889 , Acc = 34.8000 (val), Loss = 1.7612, Acc = 36.825 (test)
One can see that the losses are now bigger in training and validation set but smaller in the test set. Simultaneously, the Accuracy of train and validation set are now lower than in the first model but bigger on the test set with the second approach. The model learns and is more capable in classification. Also, the learning rate value changed for the best performing model.

> Weights of new model:
The visualization of the weights has clearly changed. We see that more meaningful features are being learned and can see some light patterns on the weight visualization (especially visible on Class 2, Class 7 pictures).
